  <p data-reveal>When I bring up nervous system regulation with people who come to session, there's almost always a moment of initial confusion. The word "regulation" sounds technical, clinical, a little cold. But what it points to is something very concrete and very human: the body's capacity to move fluidly between different states of activation depending on what the real situation calls for, and to return to rest once the threat has passed.</p>
  <p data-reveal>It's not the same as calming down. It's not control. It's not the absence of emotion. And understanding that distinction profoundly changes how a person can relate to their own inner system.</p>
  <h2 data-reveal>What "regulating" actually means</h2>
  <p data-reveal>The autonomic nervous system operates continuously, outside deliberate awareness. It detects signals of safety or threat in the environment and inside the body, and adjusts the physiological state accordingly. Stephen Porges, with his <a href="/en/blog/polyvagal-theory/" class="link-underline">Polyvagal Theory</a>, described with precision the different states this system can inhabit: from sympathetic activation — fight or flight — to dorsal vagal collapse, where the organism shuts down to survive. And between those extremes, a state Porges calls ventral vagal: the platform from which we can learn, connect, create, feel curiosity, be present.</p>
  <p data-reveal>Deb Dana, who has translated polyvagal theory into accessible clinical practice, puts it in a way I find very useful: regulation isn't a fixed state of calm. It's the capacity to return. To return to balance after agitation. To return to presence after numbness. A regulated person isn't one who never activates — that would be dissociation, not health — but one who can come back.</p>
  <p data-reveal>When the nervous system is well regulated, that ventral vagal platform is available. When it's dysregulated, it isn't. And from a state of chronic dysregulation, many of the things that matter most to us — close relationships, creative work, learning, the capacity to feel joy — become hard to access, not for lack of willpower, but because the operating system we're running on isn't in a condition to sustain them.</p>
  <h2 data-reveal>What dysregulation looks like in daily life</h2>
  <p data-reveal>Chronic dysregulation doesn't always look the way we imagine. It isn't always a visible panic attack or crisis. Very often it's quieter: emotional reactivity that seems disproportionate to small situations, persistent difficulty concentrating, a sense of being disconnected or moving through your days without really being present. A body that can't "switch off" to sleep, even when the exhaustion is real. Emotional outbursts followed by guilt, or collapses that arrive without warning.</p>
  <p data-reveal>This connects directly to <a href="/en/blog/chronic-stress/" class="link-underline">chronic stress</a>, to <a href="/en/blog/somatic-anxiety/" class="link-underline">somatic anxiety</a>, and to what I sometimes call <a href="/en/blog/undiagnosed-trauma/" class="link-underline">undiagnosed trauma</a>: experiences that don't necessarily fit the classic definition of trauma, but that left the nervous system in a state of permanent alert that never fully resolved.</p>
  <p data-reveal>What I think is important to underline is that none of these states is a personal failure. They're learned responses. The nervous system did what it knew how to do to keep us safe in contexts where safety was scarce or unpredictable. The problem isn't that it learned wrong — the problem is that those responses stayed active long after the original circumstances changed.</p>
  <h2 data-reveal>How regulation is worked with in therapy</h2>
  <p data-reveal>The good news is that the nervous system is plastic. It can learn. And that learning happens, primarily, in relationship.</p>
  <p data-reveal>Porges pointed to something that changed how I understand my own work: the therapeutic relationship itself is the first context of regulation. When two people are in co-presence, their nervous systems synchronize. A therapist who can inhabit the ventral vagal state — who is genuinely present, without urgency or judgment — offers the other person's nervous system a safety signal that, sometimes, they've never received in a sustained way before. That's not rhetoric. That's neurophysiology.</p>
  <p data-reveal>From that foundation, there are concrete tools I work with. <a href="/en/blog/somatic-experiencing/" class="link-underline">Somatic Experiencing</a>, developed by Peter Levine, works from inside the nervous system: it helps track the physical sensations associated with activation states, complete defensive responses that were left incomplete, and let the organism discharge what it's been carrying. <a href="/en/blog/tapping-eft/" class="link-underline">Tapping / EFT</a> offers a different way in: stimulating acupressure points while activating emotional material can interrupt the activation circuit and reorganize the nervous system's response to that content. <a href="/en/blog/body-based-therapy/" class="link-underline">Body-based therapy</a> works with the body as the point of entry, recognizing that patterns of tension, posture, and movement are also patterns of the nervous system.</p>
  <p data-reveal>And there's something more: a good part of the work happens between sessions. I can teach you concrete practices — not generic techniques, but tools calibrated to your system, your history, how dysregulation shows up in your particular case — so the process doesn't depend only on the weekly hour of therapy, but starts living in your everyday life.</p>
  <p data-reveal>Regulating the nervous system isn't a luxury or a weekend wellness practice. It's the foundation from which everything else — relationships, work, personal growth, the capacity to be present in your own life — becomes possible. Your capacity to regulate isn't lost. In most cases, it's just blocked. And that has a way forward.</p>
  <p data-reveal>If you want to know what it would be like to start this work, you can read about the <a href="/en/blog/first-session/" class="link-underline">first session</a> or explore whether this is a <a href="/en/blog/good-time-to-start/" class="link-underline">good time for you</a>.</p>
